INSERT INTO public."Documents" (doc_id, inst_coll_proj_id, digitalizo_collab_id, document_internal_id, title, description, transcribio_collab_id) VALUES (170, 1, NULL, 'HPKraus_079', 'Royal cedula to Martín Enríquez, Viceroy of New Spain', '''- The archbishop of Mexico, Pedro Moya de Contreras, had reported to the King that the Franciscan, Dominican, and Augustinian Orders in Mexico, not content with the number of towns to which they ministered in the archdiocese, were daily entering the towns of secular priests and persuading the Indians to obey the friars rather than the secular priests, which the Indians did easily because of the great influence of the friars. This was causing disagreements between the friars and the secular clergy and setting a bad example for the natives. The archbishop maintained that the friars were unable to give adequate care to the towns they already had; many of the small towns were visited only occasionally, and the sick had to be brought to the friaries for confession, even though the distance was three or four leagues, and some had died on the road; the same thing occurred with children to be baptized. The archbishop asked that the friars be forbidden from taking over towns or areas subject to secular clergy and that he be allowed to place secular clergy in towns which the friars had taken over but which did not have friaries; the Viceroy should also be prohibited from giving such towns to the friars. The archbishop''s report was considered by the Council of the Indies and, after consultation with the King, this cedula was issued, commanding the Viceroy to investigate the legislation that had previously been issued in this regard and to see that it was carried out.
INSERT INTO public."Documents" (doc_id, inst_coll_proj_id, digitalizo_collab_id, document_internal_id, title, description, transcribio_collab_id) VALUES (176, 1, NULL, 'HPKraus_084', 'Royal letter to [Diego Romano], bishop of Tlaxcala', '''- In answer to the bishop''s letter of March 20, 1576, the King approves of his having filled the benefices of the diocese in accord with the royal right of patronage and encourages the bishop to continue showing such care. The bishop had complained that the secular clergy of the diocese were being molested unnecessarily by being summoned to Mexico for every Indian complaint, and he had asked the King to let him judge such matters. Accompanying this letter the King is sending a cedula to the audiencia, ordering a detailed report on the matter.
INSERT INTO public."Documents" (doc_id, inst_coll_proj_id, digitalizo_collab_id, document_internal_id, title, description, transcribio_collab_id) VALUES (177, 1, NULL, 'HPKraus_085', 'Royal cedula to [Pedro Moya de Contreras], archbishop of Mexico', '''- The King had been advised of irregularities in the ceremonies in the cathedral of Mexico. The canons were refusing to dress as deacons but were sending in their place prebendaries to say the Gospel, and for the Epistle they were sending half-prebendaries. The half-prebendaries had formerly accompanied the celebrant when he went to the sacristy to get the cope for the prayer at Vespers, but now they want chaplains to do so; at times the celebrant is accompanied only by altar boys. The King charges the archbishop to keep in mind the proper observance and to see that the services are carried out with propriety.
INSERT INTO public."Documents" (doc_id, inst_coll_proj_id, digitalizo_collab_id, document_internal_id, title, description, transcribio_collab_id) VALUES (187, 1, NULL, 'HPKraus_094', 'Royal cedula to [Pedro Moya de Contreras], archbishop of Mexico', '''- The King had been informed that, even though the archbishop was ordered not to assign priests to Indian towns for which they did not know the language, he had assigned to these towns many secular clergy who were unfamiliar with the native language. Because there were fines established for those priests who did not know the language, they learned a few words from the confessionaries, enough to enable them to hear confessions but insufficient to teach, preach to, or correct the Indians. If this is so, the archbishop can neither fulfill the duties of his office nor hope for an improvement among the Indians. He is charged, therefore, not to appoint priests who do not know well the language of the Indians over whom they have charge. Doing this, he will serve God, fulfill his duty, and give satisfaction to the King.
INSERT INTO public."Documents" (doc_id, inst_coll_proj_id, digitalizo_collab_id, document_internal_id, title, description, transcribio_collab_id) VALUES (188, 1, NULL, 'HPKraus_151B', '[Reglas y Constituciones que han de gu]ardar los Señores Inquisidores, Fiscales, Secretarios, Officiales, Calificadores, Consultores, Abogados, Comissarios, Notarios, Honestas personas, Capellanes, Familiares y otros qualesquier Ministros del Tribunal del', '''- The Cofradía de Señor San Pedro Martir was the brotherhood which was made up of all the members of the Inquisition, from the Inquisitors down to the least of the lay ministers. In 1657 the fraternity in Mexico City apparently was reorganized by order of the visitor of the Inquisition, Pedro de Medina Rico. The present volume begins with an order by Medina Rico and the three Inquisitors, issued in Mexico City on October 23, 1657, to the effect that the members should meet regularly to become acquainted with their rights, privileges, and obligations and to elect the head of the fraternity. The order is signed by Medina Rico and by the Inquisitors Francisco de Estrada y Escobedo, Juan Sáenz de Mañozca, and Bernabé de la Higuera y Amarilla and is countersigned by the secretary Eugenio de Saravia.
INSERT INTO public."Documents" (doc_id, inst_coll_proj_id, digitalizo_collab_id, document_internal_id, title, description, transcribio_collab_id) VALUES (196, 1, NULL, 'HPKraus_099', 'Copy of a royal cedula to the audiencia of La Plata de los Charcas, Upper Peru', '''- The Crown had ordered the founding of a university in Lima for the education of the colonists, and the King is pleased that it is showing good results. One of the King''s principal aims was to improve the welfare of the Indians; therefore, a chair had been established for the training of priests in the Indian language, which was necessary for fulfilling their office. The King commands that such a chair be established in every city where there is an audiencia, and he issues the appropriate ordinances for their establishment.
INSERT INTO public."Documents" (doc_id, inst_coll_proj_id, digitalizo_collab_id, document_internal_id, title, description, transcribio_collab_id) VALUES (765, 1, NULL, 'HPKraus_122/1', 'Deed of sale of land to Bartolomé Dávila', '''- In this document written on vellum, Pero Riquel, vecino of the city of Jerez de la Frontera, records the sale of two and a half caballerías of land to Bartolomé Dávila, son of the deceased jurado Martín Dávila and also a vecino of Jerez. The piece of land, which lay between the lands of the heirs of Alvar Núñez Cabeza de Vaca and of Diego de Roca, had been sold to Dávila by Riquel during September 1511, with the understanding that upon Dávila''s request Riquel would have a deed drawn up. The price of the land was 200,000 maravedis, and the owner had the added obligation of paying an annual tribute or tax of 915 maravedis, one mutton, and two cheeses to the canons of the Church of San Salvador of Jerez. The deed was drawn up in the house of Doctor Francisco Rodríguez Lucero, who witnessed it together with Luis Ortiz de Gatica, teniente de almirante, and Pedro de Molina, royal notary. It was notarized by Antón de Alarcón, notary public of Jerez. This deed is followed by a fragment of the record of the act of taking possession of the property by Bartolomé Dávila in the presence of Antón de Alarcón on July 6, 1512. From this fragment it appears that the piece of land was also bordered by lands of the Carthusian monastery and of the Church of San Dionys.
INSERT INTO public."Documents" (doc_id, inst_coll_proj_id, digitalizo_collab_id, document_internal_id, title, description, transcribio_collab_id) VALUES (620, 4, NULL, 'AGI_CONTRATACION_1178_N1_R1', 'Registro del navío: varios', 'Registro de ida de los siguientes navíos, que fueron con la flota de Nueva España, a cargo del general Miguel de Chazarreta:
INSERT INTO public."Documents" (doc_id, inst_coll_proj_id, digitalizo_collab_id, document_internal_id, title, description, transcribio_collab_id) VALUES (627, 4, NULL, 'AGI_CONTRATACION_488_N3_R17', 'Bienes de difuntos: Hernando de Vergara', 'Diligencias sobre los bienes del difunto Hernando de Vergara, piloto de la nao Santa Catalina, maestre Alonso de Buenavista, una de las de la flota del general Antonio Navarro. La nave se perdió el 2 de noviembre de 1590 con gran tormenta dentro de San Juan de Ulúa, aunque se trató de salvar echando anclas. Algunos de sus tripulantes, incluidos el piloto, el maestre, el capitán/dueño (Esteban Timchel), el escribano (Miguel Ochoa), marineros y esclavos, escaparon de la nao en el batel pero la mayoría de ellos se ahogó.
INSERT INTO public."Documents" (doc_id, inst_coll_proj_id, digitalizo_collab_id, document_internal_id, title, description, transcribio_collab_id) VALUES (472, 5, NULL, 'utblac_eog_j_04_duplicated', '4. Jesuítas', 'Compañía de Jesús. Colegio de Tepozotlán. Mandamiento original del Marqués de Guadal cazar autorizando al Colegio a sacar piedra para la obra de su edificio, pero sin concederle la propiedad de la cantera
INSERT INTO public."Documents" (doc_id, inst_coll_proj_id, digitalizo_collab_id, document_internal_id, title, description, transcribio_collab_id) VALUES (489, 6, NULL, 'utblac_eog_j_01_duplicated', '1. Jesuítas.', 'Compañía de Jesús. Colegio de Te pozotlán. Mandamiento original del Virrey Conde de la Coruña. Aprueba la donación que hicieron los indios de Tepozotlán a la Compañía de Jesús para establecer el Colegio. En seguida el aca de posesión. Cuautitlán, 5 de julio -1582.
INSERT INTO public."Documents" (doc_id, inst_coll_proj_id, digitalizo_collab_id, document_internal_id, title, description, transcribio_collab_id) VALUES (505, 7, NULL, 'Expediente 2', 'Los indios de Xochimilco contra los indios de Culhuacan sobre mojoneras y términos (1573-1575).', 'Se trata de un litigio entre los gobernantes y principales colhuas contra los señores gobernantes y principales de Xochimilco en la región sur de Colhuacan. El problema comenzó con los xochimilcas de la cabecera de Tepetenchi, pero posteriormente litigaron los de la cabecera de Olac y Tecpan. Antiguamente hubo un conflicto en la misma zona en 1541, en el expediente se incluyó un trasunto del decreto del oidor Alonso Maldonado cuando estableció los límites el 17 de abril de dicho año. En ambos procesos son los colhuas quienes denunciaron a los xochimilcas de invadir sus tierras.
INSERT INTO public."Documents" (doc_id, inst_coll_proj_id, digitalizo_collab_id, document_internal_id, title, description, transcribio_collab_id) VALUES (507, 11, NULL, 'JGI_XXV-01_Tenamaztlan', 'Relación de Tenamaztlan', 'Description of Tenamaztlan, located in the Diocese of Guadalajara. Signer of census is Pedro de Ávila. Document lists Mexicana and two unidentified languages as the spoken languages, surrounding towns such as Cocula, Ayutla, Tepantla, and Zoyatlan, topographic features, and flora and fauna. Also mentioned are descriptions of the native population, local jurisdiction, hierarchy, and systems of governance, etymology of names, medicines used, and architecture. This is one of a series of responses to a political and cultural survey circulated by King Philip II of Spain titled relaciones geográficas, which were gathered between the years 1579-1585.
INSERT INTO public."Documents" (doc_id, inst_coll_proj_id, digitalizo_collab_id, document_internal_id, title, description, transcribio_collab_id) VALUES (508, 11, NULL, 'JGI_XXIV-05_Hueytlalpa', 'Relación de Hueytlalpa', 'Description of Hueytlalpa as well as full descriptions of the surrounding towns located in the Diocese of Tlaxcala. Surrounding towns include Zacatlan, Xuxupango, Matlatlan y Chila, Papantla, Tecolutla, and Tenanpulco y Matlactonatico. Census was signed by Juan de Carrión. Document lists Mexicana and Totonaco as the languages spoken, fauna, etymology of place names, and topographic features of the land such as rivers and roads.  Descriptions place these communities in a historical, geographical, and cultural context within the larger province of Zacatlan and provides details on native population, and systems of governance.  Also included are multiple visual representations of the landscape, known as pinturas or maps. This is one of a series of responses to a political and cultural survey circulated by King Philip II of Spain titled relaciones geográficas, which were gathered between the years 1579-1585.
INSERT INTO public."Documents" (doc_id, inst_coll_proj_id, digitalizo_collab_id, document_internal_id, title, description, transcribio_collab_id) VALUES (510, 11, NULL, 'JGI_XXIV-11_Justlahuaca', 'Relación de Justlahuaca', 'Description of the administrative capital of Justlahuaca and several other towns found in this part of the Diocese of Oaxaca within the province of Mixteca Baja. Census was signed by Andrés Aznar de Cózar. Document includes complete descriptions of the towns of Mixtepeque, Ayusuchiquilazala,  Xicayan, Puctla, and Zacatepeque. Descriptions place these communities in a historical, geographical, and cultural context within the larger province of Mixteca Baja. Details include Amuzgo, Mixteca, and Mexicana as the spoken languages, etymology of place names, building construction, natural resources, flora and fauna of the surrounding area, and the local systems of governance. This is one of a series of responses to a political and cultural survey circulated by King Philip II of Spain titled relaciones geográficas, which were gathered between the years 1579-1585.
INSERT INTO public."Documents" (doc_id, inst_coll_proj_id, digitalizo_collab_id, document_internal_id, title, description, transcribio_collab_id) VALUES (516, 11, NULL, 'JGI_XXIV-17_Queretaro', 'Relación de Querétaro', 'Description of Querétaro, located in the Diocese of Michoacan. Signer of census is unknown. Document lists Mexicana and Otomí as the spoken languages, topographic features, and flora and fauna. Also included are details of the native population, province, local jurisdiction, hierarchy, and systems of governance, etymology of names, medicines used, hospitals, and monasteries and convents. The census makes reference to the creation of an accompanying map, but it is not included in the Joaquín García Icazbalceta Manuscript Collection. This is one of a series of responses to a political and cultural survey circulated by King Philip II of Spain titled relaciones geográficas, which were gathered between the years 1579-1585.
INSERT INTO public."Documents" (doc_id, inst_coll_proj_id, digitalizo_collab_id, document_internal_id, title, description, transcribio_collab_id) VALUES (526, 11, NULL, 'JGI-XXV-07_Tiripitio', 'Relación de Tiripitio', 'Description of Tiripitio, located in the Diocese of Michoacan. Census was signed by Fray Guillermo de Santa María and Pedro de Montes de Oca. Document lists Tarasca as the spoken language, topographic features,  medicines used, and flora and fauna. Document also contains pages of correspondence, including from Montes de Oca dated 1580 and Fray Guillermo de Santa María dated 1580. Also mentioned are descriptions of the local hierarchy and systems of governance, etymology of names, architecture, farms, churches, hospitals, and monasteries and convents. This is one of a series of responses to a political and cultural survey circulated by King Philip II of Spain titled relaciones geográficas, which were gathered between the years 1579-1585.
INSERT INTO public."Documents" (doc_id, inst_coll_proj_id, digitalizo_collab_id, document_internal_id, title, description, transcribio_collab_id) VALUES (527, 11, NULL, 'JGI_XXIV-19_Tecuicuilco', 'Relación de Tecuicuilco', 'Description of Tecuicuilco and surrounding towns in the Diocese of Oaxaca. Census is signed by Francisco de Villagar. Document lists Zapoteca as the spoken language, full descriptions of the surrounding towns such as Yetía, Guaxilotitlan, Atepeque, Zoquiapa and Xaltianguiz, topographic features, and flora and fauna. There are also details of the local jurisdiction, hierarchy, and systems of governance, medicines used, etymology of names, churches, and architecture. Also included is a visual representation of the landscape, known as a pintura or map. This is one of a series of responses to a political and cultural survey circulated by King Philip II of Spain titled relaciones geográficas, which were gathered between the years 1579-1585.
INSERT INTO public."Documents" (doc_id, inst_coll_proj_id, digitalizo_collab_id, document_internal_id, title, description, transcribio_collab_id) VALUES (529, 11, NULL, 'JGI_XXIII-08_Acapistla', 'Relación de Acapistla', 'Description of the administrative capital Acapistla and its surroundings, located in the Archdiocese of Mexico. Census was signed by alcalde mayor Juan Gutiérrez de Liébana. Document details the history of Acapistla, the etymology of its name and other community names within its jurisdiction, lists Mexicana as the language spoken, natural resources, flora and fauna, locations of churches and monasteries, and Acapistla''s location within the Archdiocese of Mexico. Also mentioned are the sixteen smaller communities found within the jurisdiction of Acapistla, which are Texcala, Atlitiqui, Suchitlan, Zuquiapa, Ayapanco, Itlacan, Tecaxiqui, Tecocuzpa, Zahuatlan, Tetliculuca, Calalpa, Ecatepeque, Zacatepeque, Atlahuymulco, and Pazulco. Also included is a visual representation of the landscape, known as a pintura or map. This is one of a series of responses to a political and cultural survey circulated by King Philip II of Spain titled relaciones geográficas, which were gathered between the years 1579-1585.
INSERT INTO public."Documents" (doc_id, inst_coll_proj_id, digitalizo_collab_id, document_internal_id, title, description, transcribio_collab_id) VALUES (536, 11, NULL, 'JGI_XXIV-12_Meztitlan', 'Relación de Meztitlan', 'Description of the provincial capital of Meztitlan and its surroundings, located in the Archdiocese of Mexico. Responses describe the history of the community, the division of surrounding provinces and their respective government officials, and the land itself listing native species of flora and fauna. Also included is an extensive description of the religious orders in the area with the most active being the Order of Saint Augustine.  A description of the topographic features of the land is included along with a description of the rivers and other water sources. The smaller towns located in province are also described, which include Xelitla, Fuerte de Xalpa, Chicontepec, Guaxulla, Llamaltlan, Chapulhuacan, Tlanchinolticpac, Yagualíca, Hueyacocotlan, Molango, Suchicoatlan, Tzaqualtipan, and Malila. At the start of the manuscript is an illustration depicting the method of recording time in the Aztec calendar. Also included is a visual representation of the landscape, known as a pintura or map. This is one of a series of responses to a political and cultural survey circulated by King Philip II of Spain titled relaciones geográficas, which were gathered between the years 1579-1585.
INSERT INTO public."Documents" (doc_id, inst_coll_proj_id, digitalizo_collab_id, document_internal_id, title, description, transcribio_collab_id) VALUES (545, 11, NULL, 'JGI_XX-09_Zapotitlan', 'Relación de Zapotitlan', 'Description of Zapotitlan, province in the Diocese of Guatemala. Census is signed by Juan de Estrada. Document lists Mexicana as well as other Guatemalan languages as the spoken languages, topographic features, surrounding towns such as Xicalpa, Izapa, Patzicía, Patzum, and Tolimán Alto, medicines used, and flora and fauna. There is also description of the native population, local jurisdiction, hierarchy, and systems of governance etymology of names, architecture, farms, churches, hospitals, ports, and monasteries and convents. Also included is a visual representation of the landscape, known as a pintura or map. This is one of a series of responses to a political and cultural survey circulated by King Philip II of Spain titled relaciones geográficas, which were gathered between the years 1579-1585.
INSERT INTO public."Documents" (doc_id, inst_coll_proj_id, digitalizo_collab_id, document_internal_id, title, description, transcribio_collab_id) VALUES (644, 14, NULL, 'AGI_INDIFERENTE_2053_N83   Fernandez145-MEX16-EMJ-VAG-CCC', '463. De Pedro de Robles a su hijo, Juan Robles, en Sevilla aunque es natural de León', 'Pedro de Robles pide se le ayude a encontrar a su hijo, Juan Robles, que dejó pequeño antes de irse a América, y a recibir un título de escribano que ha solicitado.
INSERT INTO public."Documents" (doc_id, inst_coll_proj_id, digitalizo_collab_id, document_internal_id, title, description, transcribio_collab_id) VALUES (649, 14, NULL, 'Fernandez201-MEX16-EMJ-VAG-CCC', '585. De Juan de Brihuega, mercader de paños, a su cuñado, Pedro García, maestro de hacer paños, en Brihuega (Guadalajara)', 'El mercader Juan de Brihuega le comenta a su cuñado Pedro García la muerte de dos hijos suyos y el nuevo embarazo de su esposa, le explica que tiene mucho trabajo y, aunque tiene contratados a varios negros, necesita que se vayan a vivir con él cuanto antes.
INSERT INTO public."Documents" (doc_id, inst_coll_proj_id, digitalizo_collab_id, document_internal_id, title, description, transcribio_collab_id) VALUES (667, 14, NULL, 'Fernandez358-MEX16-GHT-JGR-CCC', '166. De Gaspar de Arciniega a su hermano Francisco de Arciniega, natural de Frías (Burgos)', 'Gaspar de Arciniega se queja a su hermano Francisco de Arciniega por no haberle escrito aunque sabe noticias suyas, le pide que vaya con él y que le informe de su vida y de la de los otros hermanos; además, da cuenta de su vida y pide una ejecutoria.
INSERT INTO public."Documents" (doc_id, inst_coll_proj_id, digitalizo_collab_id, document_internal_id, title, description, transcribio_collab_id) VALUES (678, 14, NULL, 'Fernandez415-MEX16-JGR-VAG-CCC', '407. Del conde de Coruña, virrey y capitán general de Nueva España, a su mayordomo, Diego de las Cuevas de Zúñiga, en Guadalajara', 'El conde de Coruña, visorrey y capitán general de Nueva España, escribe a su primo y mayordomo, Diego de las Cuevas de Zúñiga, en respuesta a una carta suya en que le cuenta que no ha podido viajar porque estaba enfermo y le pide permiso para que le acompañen algunos criados.
INSERT INTO public."Documents" (doc_id, inst_coll_proj_id, digitalizo_collab_id, document_internal_id, title, description, transcribio_collab_id) VALUES (688, 14, NULL, 'Fernandez492-MEX16-JGR-VAG-CCC', '207. De Diego de Castañeda a su hermano Hernando de Castañeda, vecino de Osuna (Sevilla)', 'Diego de Castañeda da cuenta de su vida en América a su hermano Hernando de Castañeda, y le ruega que viaje a América con él.
INSERT INTO public."Documents" (doc_id, inst_coll_proj_id, digitalizo_collab_id, document_internal_id, title, description, transcribio_collab_id) VALUES (689, 14, NULL, 'Fernandez493-MEX16-JGR-VAG-CCC', '554. De Francisco Palacio a su sobrino, Antonio de Robles, natural de Gálvez (Toledo)', 'Francisco Palacio le explica a su sobrino Antonio de Robles que está haciendo lo posible para que su hijo obtenga una capellanía, pero que no está en su mano. Le dice que le gustaría volver pero que se ha comprado una casa y que está muy ocupado.
INSERT INTO public."Documents" (doc_id, inst_coll_proj_id, digitalizo_collab_id, document_internal_id, title, description, transcribio_collab_id) VALUES (711, 14, NULL, 'Fernandez80-MEX16-AVB-GHT-CCC', '401. De Juan Muñoz a su sobrino, Francisco Muñoz, vecino de Berzocana (Cáceres)', 'Juan Muñoz escribe a su sobrino, Francisco Muñoz, insistiéndole en que se vaya con él a América y argumenta diciendo que no debe tener miedo pues tanto se puede morir en tierra como en el mar.
